------------------------------   WHY   ---------------------------------

What's the point of this language? The point is to have
  * Lovely error messages
  * Cool syntax
  * Simplicity and no modules (I encourage circular imports)

A goal I have is to make the thorn source code as pretty as the actual 
ASCII art. See for yourself (snippet from examples/dragon/main.th)

define center_head of_type list frame as loop art xii ix
   )  (     ...7..7.....    )  (    ....7..7....     )  (   .....7..7...
  ((__))    ..776677....   ((__))   ...776677...    ((__))  ....776677..
  /o..o\    ..636636....   /o..o\   ...636636...    /o..o\  ....636636..
 ( -vv- )   .6|6776|6...  ( -vv- )  ..6|6776|6..   ( -vv- ) ...6|6776|6.
  \ __. \   ..6|666|6...   ) __ (   ...6|66|6...   / .__ /  ...6|666|6..
   )     \  ...6|||||6..  /      \  ..6||||||6..  /     (   ..6|||||6...
  /       \ ..6|||||||6. /        \ .6||||||||6. /       \  .6|||||||6..
 '         ).6|||||||||6(          )6||||||||||6(         ` 6|||||||||6.
          ' ..||||||||6.            .||||||||||. `          .6||||||||..

The source code looks nice because
  * No special characters are allowed in the code (this includes
    paranthesis) to make a nice contrast with the ASCII art blocks,
    which are made up almost entirely of special charecters.
  * Drawings are isolated in their own blocks, so they're never
    interrupted by escaped characters or colors.

The paranthesis are not needed because
  * If you know the types of everything, you don't need paranthesis.
    Function arguments can be groupd with prefix Polix notation.
  * When you don't know the type of something (because it's generic or
    whatnot), you can just provide the type.
  * Indentation acts like paranthesis in some cases, allowing you to
    pass lambdas and match expressions directly as function arguments.
    It can also help with type inference.

The error messages are lovely because
  * The errors show the highlighted line, an explenation of the error,
    the previous line for context, and as all the other stuff you'd 
    expect. But it also emphesizes what's important, hiding other noise.
  * You get both compile-time and run-time errors in the same format.
    That includes runtime errors like evaluation of an undefined or
    bottom expression.
  * There are no paranthesis, meaning all errors are found left to
    right. If you get, say, a type error at the end of a line, you
    know that everything that came before it was correct, not needing
    to worry about it. There's also no concept of misplacing
    paranthesis, which are a pain to debug in Haskell.
  * There are no warnings, only errors. Unused variables and bad
    indentation are caught before an ugly error message can surface.

--------------------------   INSTALLATION   ----------------------------

thorn has no dependencies. Assuming you have cargo and ghc, you can
build it with

  $ ./build.sh

This installs thorn (the interpriter), thorn-to-sh, and thorn-to-gif to
~/.local/bin (make sure it's in your $PATH). It also installs the fonts 
used by thorn-to-gif to ~/.local/share/thorn/fonts
                                          _    ___   _
If you have nix, there's a flake         / \   \  \ / \     
you can play around with                 \  \   \  '  /     
                                       ---`  `---\   /  ,
  $ nix develop                       /___________\  \ / \  
                                         /  /      \  /  /
or install it with                  /''''  /        \/  '''\
                                    \--.  /\        /  ----/
  $ nix profile add .                 /  /  \      /  /     
                                      \ / \  \------------
In the future, I will package          `  /   \ ___   __/   
thorn for nixpkgs.                       /  ,  \   \  \     
                                         \_/ \__\   \_/     

thorn works like a calculator. It parses and compiles the source code
into an internal representation, but afterwards also executes it,
printing the evaluated main function.

  $ thorn | thorn-to-sh  | sh             # play as a shell script
  $ thorn | thorn-to-gif | ffplay -       # play as a gif (with ffmpeg)

Note that thorn expects to find a main.th file in your working directory
or in any of its parent directories. That directory is the root of your
project.

------------------------   ALGEBRAIC TYPES   ---------------------------

Thorn has algebraic types and generics. The for_all keyword is used to
declare any type variables. Here's a demo of the list and option types

| type bool contains
|     true                             
|     false                            
|                                      
| for-all a type list contains         
|     nil                              
|     cons a list a                    
|
| for_all a type option contains
|     none
|     some a
|
| define first_bool of_type fn list bool option bool as
|     lambda input_list match input_list with
|         nil              to none
|         cons head _tail  to some head

The lambda keyword starts a lambda expression, followed by a pattern,
in which the input value will be placed. The match expression
patternmatches on a value, returning the first branch that matched.

In the last line, `cons` is a data constructor and `head/tail` are
variable names for the `a` and `list a` in the list definition. _tail
is prepended with an underscore to drop the value.

| define main of_type option bool as
|     first_bool cons true cons false nil
|
>>  some true        (thorn's output, assuming the above is in main.th)

| define main of_type option bool as first_bool nil
|
>>  none

Functions can also be generic, but I'm still figuring out the syntax
for calling a generic function whose type can't be inferred. The std/
directory has a bunch of thorn code you can read, including code for
the frame type itself. There is very little built into the language,
not even numbers (defined in std/num/nat.th as roman numerals).

-------------------------   DESTRUCTURING   ----------------------------

Consider the following function that finds the distance between
two points. Ignore the undefined types/functions.

| type point contains
|     point int int
|
| define distance of_type fn point fn point float as
|     lambda first_point lambda second_point
|         match first_point with
|             point xa ya to match second_point with
|                 point xb yb to sqrt sum
|                     squared diff xb xa
|                     squared diff yb ya

This is very verbose because we're patternmatching on all the points to
get their x and y values. However, because the point type only contains
one variant, we can actually patternmatch directly in the lambda
expression like so

| define distance of_type fn point fn point float as
|     lambda point xa ya lambda point xb yb  sqrt sum
|         squared diff xb xa
|         squared diff yb ya

In fact, lambda, match, and (in the future) let expressions all share
the same syntax and semantics for capturing variables.

More Patterns:
  VAR                        Capture the value in VAR, matches anything
  CONSTRUCTOR [PATTERN]      Constructor and PATTERNs must match
  either PATTERN PATTERN     Either branch must match (same vars)
  bind VAR Pattern           Additionally bind the pattern to a VAR
  _                          Like VAR but drops the value

---------------------------   RECURSION   ------------------------------

There is no mutation and therefore there are no loops. The only way to 
loop is to recurse or use a function that recurses.

| define main of_type nat as sum
|     three                          +----------------------+
|     succ one                       | one              = 1 |
|                                    | succ one         = 2 |
| type nat contains                  | succ (succ one)  = 3 |
|     one                            | and so on            |
|     succ nat                       +----------------------+
|
| define three of_type nat as succ succ one
|
| define sum of_type fn nat fn nat nat as
|     lambda x match x with
|         one     to succ
|         succ a  to lambda y succ sum a y    -- recursive
|
>>  succ succ succ succ one

By the way, if you look at the second to last line, the `one` branch
returns a `succ` while the 'succ a' branch returs a lambda
expression. This is because the `succ` data constructor is a function.
(succ one) is of type (nat) but (succ) is of type (fn nat nat).  All 
data constructors are curried.

------------------------   LAZY EVALUATION   ---------------------------

The whole language is lazily evaluated. Expressions are only evaluated 
when patternmatched on and evaluation starts at the main function. Here 
are some examples.

| define is_equal of_type fn nat fn nat bool as
|     lambda x lambda y match tuple x y with
|         tuple one    one     to true               .----.----.----.
|         tuple succ a succ b  to is_equal a b       ['   |'   |'   ]
|         _                    to false            .--.   :    :   .--.
|                                                  |' |---.----.---|' |
| type tuple_of_nats contains                      |  |___|____|___|  |
|     tuple nat nat                                :__|            :__|
|
| define infinity of_type nat as succ infinity

Let's see the results of evaluating the following expressions. I won't
bother writing `define main of_type bool as` for each of them.

| is_equal                       -- Despite infinity being infinitely
|     succ succ succ one         -- large, we can still work with it
|     infinity                   -- because it's evaluated lazily.
|
>>  false

| is_equal                       -- Despite working with two "infinite"
|     infinity                   -- structures, and is_equal being
|     infinity                   -- recursive, the program does not
|                                -- eat memory as it hangs.
>>  *hangs at runtime*

| is_equal                       -- ... is syntax for undefined. It
|     succ one                   -- can be used in place of any
|     succ succ succ ...         -- expression.
|
>>  false

| is_equal                       -- If ... is evaluated, the program
|     succ succ succ one         -- crashes with an error message
|     succ succ ...              -- pointing to it.
|
>>  *runtime error*

---------------------------   ART BLOCKS   -----------------------------

The art macro is expanded into regular thorn code during the
tokenization phase. This code defines an animation of a swinging tail.
The animation is 6x4 in size and has 2 frames.

| include video
|
| define main of_type list frame as dragon_tail
|
| define dragon_tail of_type list frame as art vi iv
|  \   ).6|||6(   / 6|||6.
|   ) / ..6|6. \ (  .6|6..
|  ( /  .6|6..  \ ) ..6|6.
|   V   ..6...   V  ...6..

Every frame is made up of who rectangles, one with the ASCII art and
the other with the corresponding colors. Colors 0-7 correspond to ANSI
colors black-white and `|`/`.` distinguish between spaces and
transparency. The `vi iv` after the art keyword are the width and height
of each frame in romal numerals.

Note that the indentation rules are different for art blocks. if the
indentation of the line with 'art' is zero, so is the art's
indentation.  Otherwise it's the line's indentation + 4.  Yes, the
indentation length is hardcoded to 4. This improves error messages.

There is special syntax for including local/global variables in the
art. To use a color variable you just replace the color number with the
variable name like so

| define dragon_tail of_type fn color list frame as
|     lambda c art vi iv
|          \   ).c|||c(   / c|||c.
|           ) / ..c|c. \ (  .c|c..
|          ( /  .c|c..  \ ) ..c|c.
|           V   ..c...   V  ...c..

Now instead of the tail being hardcoded cyan, the calling function
decides its color. Here's the full table of supported art syntax.

  +------+-------+-----------------------------------------+
  | left | right |                 effect                  |
  +------+-------+-----------------------------------------+
  | CHAR | 0     | Grey                                    |
  | CHAR | 1     | Red                                     |
  | CHAR | 2     | Green                                   |
  | CHAR | 3     | Yellow                                  |
  | CHAR | 4     | Blue                                    |
  | CHAR | 5     | Magenta                                 |
  | CHAR | 6     | Cyan                                    |
  | CHAR | 7     | White                                   |
  | CHAR | VAR   | Uses VAR as the color                   |
  |      | |     | Space character                         |
  |      | .     | Transparent                             |
  | VAR  | $     | uses VAR as the character               |
  | VAR  | #     | layers the frame VAR on top             |
  | VAR  | ^     | applies fn VAR to the character below   |
  +------+-------+-----------------------------------------+
where  VAR  is a single-letter variable name
       CHAR is a visible ASCII character

You can see how the core types are implemented in the std. Ther are
many useful functions in video.th, list.th, and frame.th . To find
the definition of a function, just run

  $ grep -rn 'define function_name'

-----------------------------   OUTPUT   -------------------------------

After running thorn on the above program, the output is the
fully-evaluated main function, a tree of data constructors, a string
of words when printed out. In fact, if you copy-paste the output into
the main function, you will get the same output. To turn this output
into something you actually want, you have to interpret it with an
external program.

thorn tries to adhere to the UNIX philosophy. All programs do one thing
and their outputs are intended to be inputs for other programs. That's
how you end up with the lovely pipelines shown at the start

  $ thorn | thorn-to-sh | sh
